sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Files With System Process Name In Unsuspected Locations
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the creation of an executable with a system process name in folders other than the system ones (System32, SysWOW64, etc.).
It is highly recommended to perform an initial baseline before using this rule in production.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Sander Wiebing, Tim Shelton, Nasreddine Bencherchali (Nextron Systems)

attributes.magic: PE32 executable (GUI) Intel 80386, for MS Windows, UPX compressed

exiftool.ImageFileCharacteristics: No relocs, Executable, No line numbers, No symbols, 32-bit

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a classic mass-mailing and P2P worm, likely a variant of the Bagle malware family. It exhibits several high-confidence malicious behaviors: 1) Persistence: It installs itself into the 'Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run' registry key with the value 'Traybar'. 2) Stealth: It copies its executable to the Windows or Temp directories masquerading as 'lsass.exe'. 3) Information Stealing: It harvests email addresses by querying the Windows Address Book (WAB) registry keys and recursively scanning local files for strings containing '@'. 4) Propagation: It crawls the filesystem for directory names associated with P2P sharing (e.g., 'shar', 'download', 'incoming') to drop copies of itself. 5) Mutex-based execution control: It generates a unique mutex based on the host's name using a custom MD5 hashing implementation (sub_806cf9).
